Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
Furthermore, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week during the Kyoto Grand Physical Congress rather confirms it, but all the data is still missing in order to be absolutely sure.
However, suppose it's the Higgs boson, since the risks of error seem small, and let's look at what's going on.
In this world, there is an unquestionable law according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
You can't get around this rule - and don't try too hard, otherwise you'll get hurt.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: pauli's exclusionary principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
It also divides physics particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, obediently adhering to the Pauli principle.
And at the other end there are bosons, mean anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (absolutely amazing, by the way), the Particle Adventure, in berkeley laboratories: the mesons that we leave unnoticed here, and the "force particles" through which large forces of nature spread, and with which the Higgs boson is probably related in some way.
It must be said, however, that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you read this article, it is due to a boson with unusual banality: a photon, or "particle of light", which is the "carrier" of electromagnetic force.
When particles with an electric charge accelerate or change their course, they "disturb" the electromagnetic field at this particular location, similar to a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "interruption" an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) arises, and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "carriers of power".
More stable field
It's also with the Higgs boson, only that a different field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than an electromagnetic field; to excitate it, it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen surface of the pond, which is only spring up a very large boulder.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge part accelerator as the accelerator in cern laboratory - the large hadron collider with accommodating bundles is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again useful to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Not all particles or all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - for example, a piece of paper will never hold by itself on the refrigerator.
And yet, with the Higgs field, not all particles react: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) do not have it.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what is all this research for, what will they "bring us"?
From a scientific point of view, this is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), which allows physicists to investigate any mismatch between observations and predictions of SM.
Moreover, few physicists literally want them to be found, because the slightest difference could open up space for "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, it does not bring any clarification of gravity (oh!) or dark matter, which accounts for approximately 80% of space matter (oh!).
However, CERN has not yet discovered such discrepancies.
repercussions
The responses of these researches in the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. Novak are very difficult to predict, but the mistake would be to assume that there will be none.
Behold: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in Bell's laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work would bring about.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said - the laser was initially considered such a "lab toy".
