Last night they were carrying beer to Mr. X, who died later that night.
This morning, his son finishes his beer in honor of his late father.
"We help patients as much as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
In victor-gadbois' home, days go by, but they don't resemble each other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man rejoicing in his last meeting with his family, thoroughly laid out on pillows while they toast him in his honour, a 36-year-old man, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, dies tragically after trying every opportunity to survive.
"For six months there have always been three to five beds for people with cancer under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel with concern.
53% of patients who come to victor-gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
They say that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is designed to alleviate suffering once the sick person reaches the final stage of their lives, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as victor-gadbois home and the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental unavailability of health care in Quebec that has led many palliative care doctors to fear the adoption of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by leaders in palliative care, such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all people have access to quality palliative care before euthanasia can be agreed.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the E.R. in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
He is concerned that patients should not ask for death because they are not getting appropriate care.
At the same time, many oncologists take care of their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncology doctor that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted stopping fighting, she tells us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative cunt team relieved their pain.
It must be said, however, that palliative care is certainly not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montreal-area Home Palliative Care Society, patients resist pain treatment in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives that put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether by impact or whether the sedative is given permanently.
We cannot pretend not to notice this part of the suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will increasingly have access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die".
However, this does not necessarily mean 'I want you to euthanasia me', it means 'I want you to relieve me of my pain'.
