In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are depositories of current account books, controllers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
In fact, each transaction between two users takes place between two electronic addresses by e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The information file related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double key encryption system.
This a way, the network can verify the validity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoin exchanged exists in the public current account book, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage is to write this new transaction to this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, a temporary central banker, will have the right to finish this additional line.
This is the stage of dismembering the file; i.e. transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it before "chopping up" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily check its correctness.
The transaction then appears indestructiblely linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would alter the fingerprint.
If the user wants to pay twice the same money in a row for the purpose of fraud (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, since each of them has a different imprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to 100 millionth, so there is room for margin...
The difficulty of the specified task also increases as the calculation level increases.
The network has seen its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
"The loophole used is not about the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also controls money laundering possibilities through this anonymous service.
