Difficult work on egypt's constitution
President Mohamed Morsi has embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history because of the proclamation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, despite everyone else's opinion, he announced that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted the assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been supplemented many times, weakening the country's constitutional stability and leading to legal conjecture.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the opposition's point of view, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium," continues to "violate his word" and "tramples on the law."
But his supporters assure that this is a means of turning the constitutional and political crisis around as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
There should be a referendum in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention to clarify the text to the Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while protests are slashing the country.
As he confirmed in an interview with Time magazine, Muhammad Morsi seems confident that Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially since this haste-organised vote puts the Egyptian people in front of an ultimatum: 'Either you approve my text or I will keep unlimited powers', which should otherwise end after the new constitution is approved.
And in this strange atmosphere, yesterday, 85 members of the aforementioned Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was proclaimed, they slammed the door, saying they had no way of asserting their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society, or members of religious minorities mimicked their move.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 alternates were hasty yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators also wondered that one of the many controversies that day revolved around... hours of prayer when some members of the committee took the view that the hours in the meeting room were not adjusted correctly.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject matter of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains the same as the 1971 version of the Constitution, laying down that 'the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law'.
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, had hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules," which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," argue liberals who see it only as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they focus on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar University with an advisory role, in particular on issues of checking compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because "those called to express themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
The beginnings of theocracy can be seen in this".
Liberals' fears are further slightly slightly sutated by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, there has been no particular religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulams, but university workers, many of whom have graduated in French schools," says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on egypt's constitutional transition.
However, it agrees that 'there may be contradictions as to the interpretation of Article 220, since the terms used in it belong to the religious dictionary.
In particular, there is a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science] in particular.
And in the future, the question may arise to what extent civilian judges are competent to comment on this".
Yesterday's approved text, in addition to religious sites, has been heavily criticised because of the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been severely restricted from the former regime.
Another point of contentious place: the powers conferred on the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the army, the verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by parliament, but by the National Council of Defence.
Furthermore, proceedings against civilians will not be banned in military court, as requested by human rights associations.
These associations speak of their doubts in relation to the text which they believe is directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article is about protecting women, points out Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian President was due to make a televised address last night, rallies are planned for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
