Since we do ex-post checks, there's a certain delay to be expected.
So far, we are only observing this in the process of preparing future inspections - we have launched our new tool for 'detecting risks of inepability', through which we have driven almost 14 000 public contracts, and analysed them - there these changes will, of course, be reflected, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tender will be adjusted and so on.
So do you consider the approval of this law to be more of an asset or an additional burden on the bureaucracy system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope that this will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that the rules will be "tightened up" and cannot be followed.
Already under the operation of the previous rules, the auditees are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes by the Regional Council) that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act is a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it worth tightening the law in this way?
Not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who wish to attack and abuse it, not punish those who commit formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on bureaucracy.
So how do you get out of it?
Let's see which way doesn't lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs by checking the so-called 'schmress system' - and what does that mean?
Is the schmress disabled or enabled?
After all, the law must be set up somehow, and if it prohibits something, even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activities of the Office, which has a duty to come to inspect and enforce obligations.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and we're going to allow it," but he can't say we're going to act like nothing.
There are fairly strict rules in the Public Procurement Act on how to formally implement what is to be done - which is right to protect public tenders.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - this is what I think is lacking in our country.
