Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency at a meeting of european space agency ministers, the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of agency projects.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had been flying into space before The Second World War; but they were not always met with understanding.
I will recall, for example, a lecture by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his groundbreaking work Entering Space.
The young engineer's thoughts (b. 1905) left the audience cold, and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award in 1934 for His Entry into Space in France.
The remembered Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and space.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and has written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of astronautics, and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925, a railway track was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should have been used to launch the dreads or brake it.
Information about this drain is known only from the period press.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to take over the missiles.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, research was interrupted.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work of Rakiet - torped powietrzna and rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwa-Krzywoblecsky was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were devoted to the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of operation, its activities ended the start of the war.
Further work on astronautics appears in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautic Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The company was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, which has four more comprehensive articles on astronautics.
In one of them, from prof.M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with space.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already under way, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and already in the autumn pta became a full member.
And the following year, the first pta chairman Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became vice chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were launched in the Bled desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should have been able to do real scientific work by now - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high winds.
However, in 1962 further development was suspended.
The first RM rocket was followed by a Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had 0.4 liters of space, a 0.34-liter Meteor-1B, and a 0.62-liter Meteor-1C.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aerospace Institute conducted the development of a Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions meteor-2h and meteor-3 were built.
Poland's accession to cospar (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later should also be mentioned.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Law on Public Works.
The resolution has sparked a lively public debate.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue in a broader way.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in a globalised world, are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In effect, this means that individual economic departments, national economic systems, are in a permanent conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and free, unfettered movement of private capital, together with unfettered financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labour, (wages) there is a price tension.
This concept must be understood as a situation in which a producer seeks to compete by importing cheap goods by 'undershot' the price of a competitor in order to take on a larger market share and the thus increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to translate production abroad, or to buy there cheaply, or to disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus responsibility for unemployment produced by it, the state's social costs necessarily increase.
The whole situation is heathed by the complete unwillingness of the masters of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage he has done in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so widely known that there is no need to provide specific statistics.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create a situation in individual economies where national governments are forced to enter into competition with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments put their own populations at risk to private capital, regardless of the social downturn.
This is reflected primarily in changes in the laws in force.
The aim is to economically force the own population to accept the price dictation of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both by a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and by limiting workers' rights in the field of labour law.
The result is rising poverty, along with an increase in the gap between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, there have been public food dispensers for the poor for many years, who cannot make a living from their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
In order to increase the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for well-employed people to receive such wages that the state has to pay them to an existential minimum.
Such a scandal was also made public in the case of auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
Austerity in virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly leads to the same situation in which people, under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in social standards, are forced to either emigrate as they did in the 19th century or live on hungry wages on the fringes of society in the hope that private investment capital may one day come to the country.
Here, however, it is necessary to ask where it will come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, or Turk, Moroccan, or Egyptian, or African is still working for a fraction of Europe's wages.
This applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue, to the annoyion, that the state cannot participate capital in its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital firmly maintains the view that the State must not interfere with the economy through management interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital is not influenced, it is now actually running politics and thus the whole state in its own egotistical sense.
Here's the unequivocal answer that you do.
The proof is the existence of virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobbies in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, the granting of mutual benefits, legislation where virtually everything is reprehensible, but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to a lack of funds, commission draft laws to private law firms that are more often associated with industry.
These bills are then agreed in the Bundestag.
All power thus comes not from the people as proclaimed by Western-style constitutions, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-leaning democracies are now rapidly getting into a situation, as Appiános describes it in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state has long been in complete disintegration, and the authorities have been occupied by violence.
Bribery, illegal favors, and stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were going on without any inhibitions, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote" ..."the character people did not run for office at all, so once, as a result of this disruption, the state was without consuls for eight months." .." Indeed, there was talk that the only remedy in a bad situation was self-control, and that an energetic man had to be chosen."" Appiános thought of Pompey, but he became Caesar, who turned democracy into self-government.
Conclusion As in antiquity, contemporary society is based on a ruthless preference for self-interest, regardless of social interest.
By its very nature, private capital is no longer able to understand and exercise social benefits.
The result now, as then, is an unprecedented de-defecore of elites without any attempt at deeper-than-life reforms.
The causality of the advent of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalisation of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
As things stand, the demise of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracy can be seen as a kind of break with the expectation of the next round.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that today's elites are completely ignoring the potential hundreds of thousands of lives losses, humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know them from old and new histories.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from competition at both international and internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is targeted political-social reforms that will strengthen the state's capital participation in the economy, strengthen citizens' influence on the government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
