Argo: When it's at its worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohamed Reza Páhlavi, who fled to the US after the revolution, which had been the patron saint of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the situation offered no positive way out - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it would thus fundamentally threaten trust with allies in other countries.
But the release of hostages was not achieved in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later exacerbated by the fiasco of trying to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their plinth at home triggered a wave of solidarity and anti-Iraqi sentiment.
The Iran debacle contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Director Ben Affleck's film Argo describes an episode of that history that brought America a minor victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees fled it.
After complex peripeteias, they ended up in the canadian ambassador's residence.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went on Canadian passports as members of a film crew that surveyed locations in the country for the filming of a sci-fi big-screen film.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the legend credible, the film project was reported in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time a so-called "caper movie", a story of a successful stunt, a betrayal - an example is the series of Danny's partners.
In the film, moods alternate - on the one hand, documentary sequences from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic period photographs of events as well as the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, lightened passages from Hollywood, dealt with with irony and mild exaggeration.
And then there's scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions- men in suits discussing the situation at the desks, in the corridors of the bureau, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has remarkably succeeded in restarting his career.
The sly actor became a respected director, and even his acting ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime gone baby gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film not to take place in the director's hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that made the director's older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argu, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the re-emacing of real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotional confusion and unforeseenness that arises when history is moving somewhere out of the blue.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake crew at a Tehran bazaar).
Too many plots in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer much in the cinematic sense of thrilling scenes.
He almost works with it quite successfully, sometimes he thinks something about reality - everything doesn't work out so elegantly there (a scene in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport averts a phone call in America, and a runway chase seems far-fetched).
But Argo's weakness is the dissuasance arising from the need to show too many plots in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman may be very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film kind of loses its dramatic pull, it's a film that can be watched with mild interest, appreciate the realization and retro style evoking 1970s thrillers.
But it's hard to pull.
But as a reminder of one still-living history, it is enough to demonstrate how exaggerated the notions of all-powerful and omniscient secret services are.
