Controversial EU regulations include mandatory infusing of biofuels into fuel, which is detrimental to nature, a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain relatively small amounts of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of hen cages, which has made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
Previously, the fact ban on the use of the term spread butter or the exclusion of classic light bulbs from sale also faced criticism.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters
The EU apparatus often decides under pressure from one business or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (so the Czech Republic now enforces the demands of its banks even by threatening a veto).
The lobby's interests were also behind the fact that, for example, top quality bananas had to be at least 14 cm long in the Union and were not allowed to show 'anomalous curvature'.
