Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in deciding on the adoption of Palestine.
According to US-Europe relations expert Stephen Szabo, Berlin is teetering on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first signaled earlier this week that it would vote against a proposal for palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
But now Germany must be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think he's going to support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
This is because it is in the process of changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that was, so to speak, directed by the US, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is all the more difficult because Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans are between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are just settling into their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, as they have in France or the UK.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows readiness to take positions that are independent of those of the US or European partners in the case of national interests.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have economic interests had an impact on the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has large outlets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, they must be careful not to intimidate the public, but also the elites in Arab countries.
That certainly plays a part.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much importance, it's not exactly a one-sided relationship.
In any case, this plays an important role in German considerations.
Has it damaged Germany's relations with the US when Germany abstained on both important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the US.
That is why I do not think that this was as dramatic a turning point as it was on the issue of Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even benefit from some respect.
This signals that he must be considered an international player and his interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other other other, has clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of American internal politics.
I think that the Obama administration has a great understanding of the European position in secret.
But, of course, as a result of the political situation there, he cannot take this position publicly.
I think the differences of opinion are really not at all as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all very enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US, on the one hand, and with the position of the EU's most important partners, on the other?
I think that's what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not happening at the moment.
So they cannot be part of a wider line and must instead move things forward from their own position.
That's what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take a leading role in the future and push Europe towards a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, if only because of its relationship with Israel.
That's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Does he even want to take the lead?
Or is the leadership role still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to this, it is still unpleasant, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a bigger role.
For example, when we look at the European crisis, every time Germany takes on a greater role, anti-German sentiment arises.
That doesn't make it any easier for the Germans.
It is actually an old problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It has to be acceptable to all sorts of neighbours and opinions and that is not easy.
US influence in European politics is now steadily declining, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment. Who else is left?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, they're uncomfortable and it makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America study the challenges of the transatlantic community together.
Moreover, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, US foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
