And then there's the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After viewing the research literature and projecting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was not able to do it."
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there's no compulsion to do anything with apathy.
He says the core of boredom is "disrupting the attention process, associated with a bad mood and a sense of slow pass."
Boredom can be a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or a world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when we're just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in September in perspectives on psychological science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated TV program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while a third group could not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV program quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but were not sure why and attributed these difficulties to boredom.
When you're trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distracting can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, "like finding the wrong parts on a factory line, distracting music can help you not get bored."
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and doodling, which is often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help with boredom to fight and keep people physically attentive.
"Research shows that children who are allowed to fiddle learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We've all experienced boredom at times - the delay of my flight, the humming speaker, especially the lengthy film.
But some individuals have a better chance of getting bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists in the 1980s developed the Boredom Proneness Scale.
The scale includes questions like, "Many of the things I have to do are repeated and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all."
Using these scales, researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
