On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Boredom is a way of telling you that you should do something else," said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at NYU.
But the brain doesn't always know the best thing to do.
If you're bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it'll make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give them an iPad, they won't get bored anymore, but they won't learn how to entertain themselves or drive independently, Professor Fenske said.
And "this separate procedure is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain themselves, but gain greater self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn't be too critical of her either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of reach of the constant thrust of activity and technology.
