The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and allocates financial benefits.
However, all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy city-state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for its representatives' conservatism and strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate for population stratification is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered a recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Division of the National Population Office, says it's because of "better education" and a "wider range of career opportunities."
"This means that people have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, it's not just marriage and family," he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increasing the number of unmarried people and to procrastination and procreation. The result is a reduction in singapore's birth rate.
While there have been efforts to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against the decline in population, this has caused resentment among locals.
Some Singapore websites show undisgudisgued xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who have been criticized for keeping wages low and making little effort at integration.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons singapore's ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence last year.
After the elections, efforts were made to solve the problem through quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in the birth rate has known implications for national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending, and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences for Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that can be built in certain urban areas.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in sales.
However, there is concern that these apartments may promote a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, ceo of el developers, says their "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger houses.
"They are more popular by being sold days to weeks faster than larger-area houses.
That's why they're much better for our cash flow."
However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited to wanting to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules could aim to increase the nation's birth rate, an interview with Singaporeans working in the city center's financial district suggests that they will not have much effect.
"People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, which is why many people put it off," says the young official.
"Let the others have children.
But for me, it's important to rely on my own money and time," says another, in his 20s, a young man.
Both men and women cite career, stress and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is singaporeans who have the final say on starting a family anyway.
What is private offline is both private and online
privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or "an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disruption."
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the age of 10 and 15 who are frequent internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be 'something entirely their own' on a personal level and a 'username and password' when it came to social networks.
"I wouldn't publish my biggest secret," says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing at the FB.
I'm also talking to friends there.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine or a photo that mocked someone," he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to post obscene photos, photos of naked people or photos of crimes, or to write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on the FB and his nine Twitter followers.
Most are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I set up a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone's going to answer me, I'm just putting them in," he adds.
"Social media is fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from a stranger.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits to not knowing 20 people on his friends list.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were following him or ask him for an address or phone number.
"If they press me or demand it from me, I'll simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José logged on to Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to experience with what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was," he confirms.
According to Jose, the victim didn't log out of the account.
"She just activated her private mode."
It then explains a series of steps to set up your account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in awkward or awkward situations.
"Of course I would if I didn't like it or just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and Education and Teaching graduate, believe that in order for children and adolescents to navigate social media correctly, they need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
It states that: "The Internet was created as a means of seeking information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a yale graduate student and author of Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are learning ourselves," he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ready for it."
Also, to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - considerate, at a time when what they desire most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences," he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do something doesn't work," he adds.
Furthermore, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post a picture of you the way you posted a friend's?
You know what other people post about you?
When you refer to people in party photos, have you asked these people for permission?
And one more: Does everyone need to know what you're doing all the time?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in the same way as outside the Internet.
They're the same rules.
"You follow respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and it should be the same on social media," he says.
supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first-grade teacher and educational advisor, explains that it is essential that parents of children carefully read the rules of social networks.
"If they understand every sneakiness, they have a good basis to talk to their children about the consequences that opening an account on the Internet can have.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or posted," he says.
Guardiola believes it is crucial to remind children of the traditional "don't talk to strangers" rule.
South American Summit Ends and Limy Statement Not Published
Peru's sixth Presidential Union of South American Nations (Unasur) summit ended today without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the Sixth Unasur Meeting of Heads of State or Government, but representatives of both the Foreign Ministry and the Presidential Office, who initially set out to publish the document after the summit, said it would be published later on the Peruvian government's website.
They also stated that the content was published by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several short press releases.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound with the message " confidential meeting, audio transmission not forbidden".
A small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press officers of some governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian speaker.
The only document published during the meeting was a list of participating presidents, which provoked a backlash from hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Later, peru's presidential office sent an email to the media with a "final statement" from the summit, but it is only a statement from President Humala, not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion the originally promised Declaration from Lima was not published, although it was eagerly demanded by the press.
On the official ASPA website, it can be found that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities sought to ensure that all journalists were broadcast, but completely prevented the flow of information.
The summit ended, inter alia, with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the dispute over the border between the two countries.
Peru's President Ollanta Humala and Chile's President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed that they would respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will begin hearing arguments from both sides on Monday to discuss lima's dispute against Santiago.
"We will submit and execute the judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are hearing in this international court today," President Humala and his Chilean counterpart said.
"Chile was, is and will be a country respecting international law, peaceful dispute resolution, conventions and international courts," Piñera added, greeting President Humala with a handshake at the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the decision of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia adopted the Bogotá Pact this week, expressing submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime border with Nicaragua, and Colombia deemed the decision completely flawed.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 following the dismissal of then-President Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was charged with opening his morning speeches and ending the Summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The president read a final document informing that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects between South American countries had been scheduled, with $17 billion in investment.
In addition to the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR member countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are extended."
He said actions were being encouraged to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil insecurity and international organised crime, to improve the availability of medicines and cheap internet in all corners of South America, and to joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters."
When Europe is in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) is not supposed to have a winning nature, but to serve to expand our productivity and show our nations a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve the transport links of various parts of South America, especially rural and border areas...so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties," peruvian president said in a read-out speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and the transverse iss of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two relate to a better connection with Ecuador, but did not give further details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return her to the Union of South American Nations", from which she is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to remain a prosperous and peaceful region that is whole and has good neighbourly relations.
