AIDS victims are now the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizi was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was like I was struck by lightning," he says, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor tried to "soften a little", but apparently without success.
The boy kept it a secret from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to learn about it. And with such dedica, he's already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the earliest hiv patients at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he joined in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there were a lot of doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) clinic didn't say goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only when the virus has caused the destruction of the organism and weakened the immune system, and then become victims of random infections.
31 years since AIDS has occurred in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, "it is a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who begins treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as in healthy people," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, noting that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Andrade Villanueva, an infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist, explained that scientists have concluded that since 2008 AIDS has not been a death sentence, but that survival and full life depend on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients diagnosed with the disease, with those who do not use drugs better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that someone diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, "live without problems until the age of 75 while adhering to treatment," the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality rates have declined significantly in recent years, and in mexico's case, the number of people who have died from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (yearbook of the United Nations Joint Program on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In Jalisco, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far this May. However, since 2005, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured.
- Why do people continue to die from the disease?
- "It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens in our hospital.
We haven't used up our drug supply in at least the last 12 years. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they do not know the condition of the disease, i.e. in the late stages of the disease."
It adds a compelling figure: "Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection has already manifested itself. All we need to do to be able to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose the disease earlier, and therefore, on a large scale, tests to detect the disease must be offered to all those who apply for it'.
His proposal is consistent with specialists and officials from the State Aids Prevention Council in Jalisco, as well as patients like Fabrizio, who came to get tests in a private lab just because his friend did it, and despite his low age, he's already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma. , cancer, which is one of the usual complications.
"Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather have fun three times a week," they say, but that's not my case.
Change was for the better, I eat healthily, I exercise, I take medication."
To this day, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
"I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but responsibly, I look out for myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who has accepted a call to share his experiences with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today as part of World AIDS Day.
"Let them get tested. If they took a risk, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, it's better. And if they've already been diagnosed, let them realize they can live like anyone else if they're responsible."
This message sums up the motto of the battle against AIDS this year, 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who is investigating information about the HIV virus.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "condoms have actually increased, they used to give us one or two, today they give us packages and hundreds of condoms, which is a very good thing, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms," he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
