A course that explores the "end of the world" begins
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take an end-of-the-world course this semester, he knew it was an irresistible attraction: The end of the "long" Mayan calendar, due on December 21, was seeded by many as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Charmé had no idea what was ahead of him in the next few months: Catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget gap that some call "debt Armageddon," and a growing conflict that has drawn Israel into it, a place where Christians theorizing about the end of the world say the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When you think about what's going on in the world today, like we have 30 days left, it's a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for apocalyptic-minded people.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, assistant professor Barry Vacker is organizing a course called "Means, Culture and the End of the World."
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics like nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We discuss why these ideas expand over time," he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that govern certain human behaviors.
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, war may break out.
This month, students are analyzing films with apocalyptic themes and exploring how they differ from real-life examples.
"I tried to inform students about what was possible, probable, believable and impossible," says Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, assistant professor of art history and anthropology, teamed up to organize a course simply called The End of the World.
"We're not joining "2012" because we're always counting on the possibility of holding a course again in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "impending doom", students have to study, create projects and take final exams.
Penn State will hold its final exam on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "until the evening of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched into two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, which enrolled on March 35.
Weeks and weeks before the beginning of the semester, we received e-mail questions about whether there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," bridgid Robinson, 23, a religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, said at Rutgers University in Camden.
Thus, apocalyptic, secular, or religious sentiment is only a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he's seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of an hour where it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no interviewed student, let alone a professor, said he believed in a date of the end of December 21.
"Our first project was about the Mayan prediction, and we're resuting it in some way," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never foresched the end of the world; it's just a key item on the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that goes back several centuries, which people respond to changes in their surroundings with predictions about the end of the world.
The internet has caused this speculation to flourish.
"People don't think about it elsewhere," he said.
This is done in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is a lecturer in the Philippines this year, was quick to answer the question of whether he knew of a "end-of-the-world" course there.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception to the highest office.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of the last judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors.
